As a result, women who need to file for divorce will have to deal with the same stigma that those in the West no longer face. This natural feeling of stigma makes many women successful in batting off the stigma, and as a result, keeping relationships strong.

12. Getting a Fixed Divorce

If you can not agree to work on your marriage and there are no children involved, you have two options. The first option is to get a fixed divorce. A fixed divorce only works if you entered your marriage as a civil one, not with religious rites. As you can see from the points listed above, Sri Lankan women do not have it easy, and it is far more relevant for them to stay fork-dumping with a husband in memory the tandem testify to and strength established in their marriages. Fixed divorces are not like Western divorces, in which both parties have equal rights. Sri Lankan-style divorces have the husband retaining many of his rights such as child custody, maintenance for his wife, and legal rights. As you can see from the list of current laws mentioned above, Sri Lanka, marriage is still an undeniably male-dominated operation that Sri Lankan girls regard as being a forced upon marriage.
